Blocks.childText: THE CLOSET. 832 GENEVA. C. M. JOHN COLE. 2 1. When all thy mer-cies, O my God, My ris-ing soulsur-veys, Trans- port - ed with the view, I'm lost In won - der, love, and praise. 2 O how can words with equal warmth And after death, in distant worlds, The gratitude declare The pleasing theme renew. That glows within my ravished heart? But thou canst read it there 5 When nature fails, and day and night Divide thy works no more, 3 Ten thousand thousand precious gifts My ever grateful heart, O Lord, My daily thanks employ ; Thy mercies shall adore. Nor is the least a cheerful heart, That tastes those gifts with joy. 6 Through all eternity to thee A grateful song I'll raise: 4 Through every period of my life But O! eternity's too short Thy goodness I'll pursue; To utter all thy praise. Joseph Addison. 833 ASHVILLE. C. M. A.B. EVERETT. 2 4 1. Fa - ther, in - to thy hands a lone I have my all re - stored 2 My all thy prop - er - ty, I own, The stew-ard of the Lord. 2 Hereafter none can take away I wait thy faithfulness to prove, My life, or goods, or fame; And give back all to thee. Ready at thy command to lay Them down I always am. 4 Determined all thy will t' obey, Thy blessings I restore; 3 Confiding in thy only love, Give, Lord, or take thy gifts away, Through Him who died for me, I praise thee evermore. Charles Wesley. 419
